00:01:48.310 --> 00:01:51.787
I know you've been doing some
reading about the current crisis

00:01:51.787 --> 00:01:55.150
and its relationship to ideas of
capitalism and so forth.

00:01:55.150 --> 00:02:00.799
I thought a little bit of
historical foundation would be a

00:02:00.799 --> 00:02:06.546
good thing to lead off with and
give you an idea of how old

00:02:06.546 --> 00:02:09.620
these financial crises are.
 

00:02:09.620 --> 00:02:14.780
This is a cuneiform tablet from
the old Babylonian period,

00:02:14.780 --> 00:02:16.500
roughly 1600 B.C.
 

00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:22.439
It's a loan,
so that it was created with the

00:02:22.439 --> 00:02:27.768
terms of the loan on one side,
and typically,

00:02:27.768 --> 00:02:30.128
although you can't see it from
this side,

00:02:30.128 --> 00:02:32.548
you'll have people that are
witnesses to the loan on the

00:02:32.548 --> 00:02:33.120
other side.
 

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:35.750
So debt has been around for a
long time.

00:02:35.750 --> 00:02:39.714
One interesting feature about
debt is that usually when

00:02:39.714 --> 00:02:43.018
you--if you're a lender,
you like to have some

00:02:43.018 --> 00:02:44.120
collateral.
 

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:48.354
The collateral for debts in
this time period often were

00:02:48.354 --> 00:02:49.610
human capital.
 

00:02:49.610 --> 00:02:52.781
In other words,
if you defaulted on your loan,

00:02:52.781 --> 00:02:56.940
the borrower could seize you
for three years and your family

00:02:56.940 --> 00:02:59.758
and you'd have to work the loan
off.

00:02:59.758 --> 00:03:06.668
That sort of debt slavery was
something that began quite early

00:03:06.668 --> 00:03:08.818
in human culture.
 

00:03:08.818 --> 00:03:13.467
You had--when you had--with
that debt slavery there would be

00:03:13.467 --> 00:03:18.590
periods when people would get
themselves into a terrible mess,

00:03:18.590 --> 00:03:22.014
and let's say crops failed and
lots of farmers wouldn't be able

00:03:22.014 --> 00:03:25.400
to pay off their loans,
you would have lots of the

00:03:25.400 --> 00:03:27.050
society in deep debt.
 

00:03:27.050 --> 00:03:29.859
And the king,
periodically,

00:03:29.859 --> 00:03:36.990
would decree all debts null and
void, so wiping the slate clean.

00:03:36.990 --> 00:03:42.370
So here is a fragment by edict
Samsuiluna,

00:03:42.370 --> 00:03:46.270
who was the son of Hammurabi,
who, by the way,

00:03:46.270 --> 00:03:52.904
lived in the city that Yale has
had a long time expedition to

00:03:52.904 --> 00:03:55.889
excavate called Tal Alon.
 

00:03:55.889 --> 00:04:01.596
Anyway this is releasing
everybody from bankruptcy in the

00:04:01.596 --> 00:04:03.938
form of debt slavery.
 

00:04:03.938 --> 00:04:06.697
But the issue there,
of course, is where you draw

00:04:06.697 --> 00:04:07.330
the line?
 

00:04:07.330 --> 00:04:11.127
Which debts do you release,
and if you just want to take

00:04:11.127 --> 00:04:14.443
people out of slavery,
but you want to maintain a

00:04:14.443 --> 00:04:17.689
financial system,
how do you differentiate?

00:04:17.689 --> 00:04:25.096
The solution to that problem,
at least from the view of

00:04:25.096 --> 00:04:29.985
writers in antiquity,
particularly Aristotle,

00:04:29.985 --> 00:04:35.730
who wrote about Solon,
comes in the form of another

00:04:35.730 --> 00:04:38.500
major debt crisis.
 

00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:44.024
When Solon of Athens became the
autarch, or whatever you want to

00:04:44.024 --> 00:04:48.759
call it, the leader of Athens,
it was about 600 B.C.

00:04:48.759 --> 00:04:51.190
or so, somewhere in that
timeframe,

00:04:51.190 --> 00:04:53.444
and he was brought in
because there was a terrible

00:04:53.444 --> 00:04:55.720
crisis,
much like the crises in the

00:04:55.720 --> 00:04:59.672
Middle East--
it was a period when Athenian

00:04:59.672 --> 00:05:03.490
citizens had been seized for
debts,

00:05:03.490 --> 00:05:05.439
and these were debts incurred
typically by farmers,

00:05:05.439 --> 00:05:08.240
and then they'd be sold off
outside of Athens,

00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:12.519
they'd just sell them offshore
and export these debt slaves,

00:05:12.519 --> 00:05:14.610
and it created terrible crisis.
 

00:05:14.610 --> 00:05:19.079
So, Solon was from a wealthy
family,

00:05:19.079 --> 00:05:23.680
he was elected by the--sort of
the rich people in Athens,

00:05:23.680 --> 00:05:27.673
they thought that he would
stand up for property rights and

00:05:27.673 --> 00:05:31.735
he wouldn't let the financial
system go to hell just because

00:05:31.735 --> 00:05:35.660
of the pain inflicted on the
poor portion of society.

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:39.100
What he did made nobody happy.
 

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:42.410
He said, "We're going to
preserve property rights,

00:05:42.410 --> 00:05:44.910
we're going to preserve the
right to contract,

00:05:44.910 --> 00:05:49.065
but the only thing we're going
to forbid is the right to sell

00:05:49.065 --> 00:05:52.875
yourself into slavery,"
so he drew the line at that

00:05:52.875 --> 00:05:54.470
debt slavery point.
 

00:05:54.470 --> 00:05:58.952
Ever afterwards,
people--Athenians would look at

00:05:58.952 --> 00:06:00.644
him,
he sort of was like the George

00:06:00.644 --> 00:06:02.879
Washington of Athens,
and 200 years later,

00:06:02.879 --> 00:06:07.230
people would write about this
moment in time when he made the

00:06:07.230 --> 00:06:11.435
differentiation between the
financial system and the system

00:06:11.435 --> 00:06:13.028
of human slavery.
 

00:06:13.028 --> 00:06:16.620
It was not to say that slaves
didn't exist,

00:06:16.620 --> 00:06:21.581
but the ability to contract on
your freedom was not allowed

00:06:21.581 --> 00:06:22.949
after Solon.
 

00:06:22.949 --> 00:06:26.706
I'm going to skip forward
through a lot of exciting

00:06:26.706 --> 00:06:28.209
financial history.
 

