history in the spring,

00:06:36.339 --> 00:06:38.310
so if you are interested in
those topics,

00:06:38.310 --> 00:06:41.829
I would love to have you
participate.

00:06:41.829 --> 00:06:45.591
I'm going to skip forward to
our debt crisis because I

00:06:45.591 --> 00:06:48.420
worry--
I stay up late nights worrying

00:06:48.420 --> 00:06:52.216
that we're getting ourselves
back into a debt slavery

00:06:52.216 --> 00:06:55.882
situation,
and the recent code that

00:06:55.882 --> 00:07:02.817
we--the bankruptcy code has made
it hard for people to shift off

00:07:02.817 --> 00:07:05.620
their debts,
or shake off their debts,

00:07:05.620 --> 00:07:07.079
which is the term that Solon
used.

00:07:07.079 --> 00:07:10.307
It was called
seisachtheia or something

00:07:10.307 --> 00:07:13.680
like this, a shaking off,
like an earthquake.

00:07:13.680 --> 00:07:19.697
But I'm going to skip forward
to 1892 and have you read this

00:07:19.697 --> 00:07:25.817
quote because it lets you have
some sense of where the policy

00:07:25.817 --> 00:07:30.060
for real estate,
mortgage lending in the United

00:07:30.060 --> 00:07:32.089
States might have come from.
 

00:07:32.089 --> 00:07:38.279
The occasion for this was a big
festive dinner.

00:07:38.279 --> 00:07:41.160
It might have been at
Delmonico's Restaurant,

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:43.629
I'm not sure exactly where,
I don't think it says here,

00:07:43.629 --> 00:07:47.637
but in New York and a bunch of
guys in the real estate business

00:07:47.637 --> 00:07:51.062
in New York were getting
together and they were really

00:07:51.062 --> 00:07:55.004
kicking off an attempt to create
a real estate exchange in New

00:07:55.004 --> 00:07:56.040
York City.
 

00:07:56.040 --> 00:07:59.750
And the exchange--there had
been something like a real

00:07:59.750 --> 00:08:03.949
estate exchange where properties
were listed and brokers were

00:08:03.949 --> 00:08:07.375
admitted and so forth--
the idea that they were coming

00:08:07.375 --> 00:08:09.932
to was that they needed an
exchange for real estate

00:08:09.932 --> 00:08:10.649
securities.
 

00:08:10.649 --> 00:08:15.350
The real estate securities that
we have now are--

00:08:15.350 --> 00:08:18.937
a lot of them are things
like--you've heard lots about

00:08:18.937 --> 00:08:22.923
Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac,
and subprime loans and

00:08:22.923 --> 00:08:28.339
commercial mortgage backed
securities and things like that,

00:08:28.339 --> 00:08:31.815
well these guys were thinking
about setting up exchange to

00:08:31.815 --> 00:08:36.607
trade debt,
maybe some equity too actually,

00:08:36.607 --> 00:08:38.259
in New York.
 

00:08:38.259 --> 00:08:41.649
And New York would be the
center of real estate trading.

00:08:41.649 --> 00:08:43.658
What were they going to trade?
 

00:08:43.658 --> 00:08:47.955
Well here's a picture,
just a piece of a bond of the

00:08:47.955 --> 00:08:50.649
kind they were going to trade.
 

00:08:50.649 --> 00:08:53.139
These things are incredibly
beautiful.

00:08:53.139 --> 00:08:56.855
The New York--the U.S. Bank
Note Company made bonds

00:08:56.855 --> 00:09:01.316
for--made stocks and bonds and
money for all the countries in

00:09:01.316 --> 00:09:04.988
the world,
and they had incredibly

00:09:04.988 --> 00:09:11.269
detailed filigrees and these
beautiful motifs and so forth.

00:09:11.269 --> 00:09:16.038
It wasn't to make these things
more attractive to customers.

00:09:16.038 --> 00:09:22.073
All of this detail was really
to prevent counterfeiting,

00:09:22.073 --> 00:09:27.779
because if you could
counterfeit a bond like this you

00:09:27.779 --> 00:09:31.840
could take it in and get
coupons.

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:33.350
So what's this bond?
 

00:09:33.350 --> 00:09:37.626
It's a $500 bond,
it's issued to finance

00:09:37.626 --> 00:09:43.769
something called 44 Wall Street
Corporation, and it's The

00:09:43.769 --> 00:09:47.168
Manhattan Company building.
 

00:09:47.168 --> 00:09:51.399
Well, 44 Wall Street is still a
building in Manhattan.

00:09:51.399 --> 00:09:53.711
I don't know if anybody here
might have worked there during

00:09:53.711 --> 00:09:56.155
the summer,
but there was a corporation

00:09:56.155 --> 00:10:00.278
that was set up to build and
operate one single building,

00:10:00.278 --> 00:10:03.389
and there was some equity
capital in the corporation and

00:10:03.389 --> 00:10:05.710
there was some debt in the
corporation.

00:10:05.710 --> 00:10:09.009
The debt was issued to the
public in bonds.

00:10:09.009 --> 00:10:14.765
You and I could go out and we
could buy these bonds and then

00:10:14.765 --> 00:10:17.676
the coupons,
the money that would come in

00:10:17.676 --> 00:10:20.570
from the bonds is money that
would come in based upon the

00:10:20.570 --> 00:10:23.721
rents that were being paid by
people that leased space in this

00:10:23.721 --> 00:10:25.220
44 Wall Street building.
 

00:10:25.220 --> 00:10:28.413
This is a fairly extraordinary
kind of security,

00:10:28.413 --> 00:10:32.083
particularly because we don't
have securities like this

00:10:32.083 --> 00:10:32.899
anymore.
 

00:10:32.899 --> 00:10:36.503
I mean there are some bonds
that have been issued against

00:10:36.503 --> 00:10:41.149
buildings,
and I'm thinking now of things

00:10:41.149 --> 00:10:44.706
like--
in London you had this vast

00:10:44.706 --> 00:10:49.269
project in the Canary Wharf,
and that was financed with some

00:10:49.269 --> 00:10:50.558
really interesting debt.
 

00:10:50.558 --> 00:10:53.197
But one to one,
building to bond,

00:10:53.197 --> 00:10:56.580
really we don't have in the
modern day.

00:10:56.580 --> 00:10:59.613
This one, by the way,
was issued one month or so,

00:10:59.613 --> 00:11:02.519
right after--not long after the
great crash.

00:11:02.519 --> 00:11:07.610
Here's a little bit about this
market.

00:11:07.610 --> 00:11:11.552
The market was nothing
much--this is the total

00:11:11.552 --> 00:11:17.158
cumulated amount of outstanding
debt based on the face values.

00:11:17.158 --> 00:11:19.379
The face value of that one was
$500,

00:11:19.379 --> 00:11:22.928
you'd multiply that times the
total number of bonds,

00:11:22.928 --> 00:11:27.480
you add all of those bonds that
existed up in this--

00:11:27.480 --> 00:11:29.240
these are the numbers you're
getting: $100 million,

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:31.070
$200 million and so on.
 

00:11:31.070 --> 00:11:37.953
You see that even in 1913 there
were some of these bonds being

00:11:37.953 --> 00:11:44.048
issued and then there are two
companies here that we're

00:11:44.048 --> 00:11:47.355
tracking,
New York Title &amp;

00:11:47.355 --> 00:11:51.500
Mortgage Company and Lawyer's
Mortgage Company.

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:59.389
These two companies actually
served as guarantors for debt.

00:11:59.389 --> 00:12:02.258
In particular,
actually, what they would do,

00:12:02.258 --> 00:12:05.460
about eight companies got
together--or didn't get

00:12:05.460 --> 00:12:08.928
together, but eight companies
offered a service.

00:12:08.928 --> 00:12:14.081
They would take a residential
mortgage, put a guarantee on it,

00:12:14.081 --> 00:12:18.048
and then sell that mortgage to
somebody else.

00:12:18.048 --> 00:12:24.166
Just like you have bond--one
commercial building offered

00:12:24.166 --> 00:12:28.947
through bonds,
you also had one mortgage for

00:12:28.947 --> 00:12:34.620
one house then guaranteed and
offered for sale.

00:12:34.620 --> 00:12:38.139
These firms also began to pool
these mortgages,

00:12:38.139 --> 00:12:41.918
and you'd pool together 100 or
so of these mortgages,

00:12:41.918 --> 00:12:46.378
or a thousand of these
mortgages, put a guarantee on

00:12:46.378 --> 00:12:51.100
them and then sell those pooled
claims out as bonds.

00:12:51.100 --> 00:12:55.282
So this picture represents not
just those commercial bonds that

00:12:55.282 --> 00:12:57.508
I showed you,
but also residential

00:12:57.508 --> 00:12:58.519
securities.
 

00:12:58.519 --> 00:13:02.447
And you can see what happened
is that they were coming along

00:13:02.447 --> 00:13:05.123
doing fine,
small part of the business,

00:13:05.123 --> 00:13:08.870
and then in the '20s both of
them picked up dramatically.

00:13:08.870 --> 00:13:13.278
As a matter of fact the First
World War was an important hinge

00:13:13.278 --> 00:13:17.325
point in the history of this
particular kind of financial

00:13:17.325 --> 00:13:18.408
innovation.
 

00:13:18.408 --> 00:13:21.690
The First World War was the
first U.S.

00:13:21.690 --> 00:13:25.538
war that was financed by
massive issues of war bonds,

00:13:25.538 --> 00:13:29.979
and it became your patriotic
duty to buy war bonds to finance

00:13:29.979 --> 00:13:31.090
the effort.
 

00:13:31.090 --> 00:13:36.856
When the war was over and those
bonds were reclaimed by the

00:13:36.856 --> 00:13:39.275
government,
they were paid off by the

00:13:39.275 --> 00:13:41.980
government,
people had been used to owning

00:13:41.980 --> 00:13:42.850
securities.
 

00:13:42.850 --> 00:13:46.740
A whole operation to sell these
securities had existed,

00:13:46.740 --> 00:13:54.500
a sales operation,
so then the brokers said,

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:55.990
"What else are we going to
sell?"

00:13:55.990 --> 00:14:02.730
Real estate bonds became a
really important new product.

00:14:02.730 --> 00:14:06.379
So you can see this might have
been driven by demand,

00:14:06.379 --> 00:14:11.616
actually, for investment
product in a marketing system

00:14:11.616 --> 00:14:17.350
that had grown for savings bonds
earlier during the war.

00:14:17.350 --> 00:14:21.153
Nevertheless,
you could see this stuff really

00:14:21.153 --> 00:14:24.700
take off and peak around
19--late '20s.

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:31.580
That was cumulative,
this is just new issues.

00:14:31.580 --> 00:14:36.434
There you see the drop around
the crash time even more

00:14:36.434 --> 00:14:37.808
dramatically.
 

00:14:37.808 --> 00:14:45.390
This is a picture of
those--plotting those number of

00:14:45.390 --> 00:14:53.864
new issues for commercial
bond--for commercial properties,

00:14:53.864 --> 00:14:57.730
against new buildings.
 

00:14:57.730 --> 00:15:01.832
Here we only took a look at new
buildings that were seventy

00:15:01.832 --> 00:15:05.298
meters high or so,
so we're looking at really tall

00:15:05.298 --> 00:15:06.288
buildings.
 

00:15:06.288 --> 00:15:12.332
This is a time period when--the
skyscraper was really born in

00:15:12.332 --> 00:15:17.873
the 1890s, and really got going
in the early part of the

00:15:17.873 --> 00:15:20.090
twentieth century.
 

00:15:20.090 --> 00:15:25.278
So a question that we've begun
to ask ourselves is,

00:15:25.278 --> 00:15:29.354
maybe the skyscraper was a
response to the emergence of a

00:15:29.354 --> 00:15:32.918
new capital market for fixed
income securities.

00:15:32.918 --> 00:15:38.081
Maybe the financing drove the
desire for big buildings rather

00:15:38.081 --> 00:15:40.490
than the other way around.
 

00:15:40.490 --> 00:15:44.210
I mean New York and other
cities had existed for a long

00:15:44.210 --> 00:15:48.068
time without skyscrapers and
there's a lot of interesting

00:15:48.068 --> 00:15:52.202
theory about how skyscrapers
were kind of a result of changes

00:15:52.202 --> 00:15:55.580
in zoning laws in some places
and so forth.

00:15:55.580 --> 00:15:58.702
But if you think about it,
London did fine without

00:15:58.702 --> 00:16:00.548
skyscrapers for many years.
 

00:16:00.548 --> 00:16:02.583
Paris, London,
other great capitals of the

00:16:02.583 --> 00:16:04.418
world did fine without
skyscrapers.

00:16:04.418 --> 00:16:07.994
Why would you suddenly have
these sort of immediate

00:16:07.994 --> 00:16:11.640
blossoming of skyscrapers
largely coincident with an

00:16:11.640 --> 00:16:16.360
emergence of a capital market
and ability to sell these bonds?

00:16:16.360 --> 00:16:24.538
By the way how would--is there
any way you can think of testing

00:16:24.538 --> 00:16:31.285
that theory about which--
if my theory was finance made

00:16:31.285 --> 00:16:36.340
skyscrapers or finance led to
big buildings,

00:16:36.340 --> 00:16:39.350
how would you test that theory
if you had some data?

00:16:39.350 --> 00:16:48.759
Prof: Come on guys,
let's take a shot.

00:16:48.759 --> 00:16:49.990
Will Goetzmann: Anybody?
 

00:16:49.990 --> 00:16:53.386
I'm going to cold call on
somebody, but your chance of

00:16:53.386 --> 00:16:55.759
being cold called--yes,
back there.

00:16:55.759 --> 00:16:57.298
Student:  Maybe you
could do a comparison,

00:16:57.298 --> 00:16:59.899
look at other countries where
for some reason--

00:16:59.899 --> 00:17:05.414
perhaps there is a case where
there's another country where

00:17:05.414 --> 00:17:10.358
the capital markets didn't
mature in the same way.

00:17:10.358 --> 00:17:13.873
I mean there's going to be some
endogeneity issues anyway with

00:17:13.873 --> 00:17:15.675
this study,
but that's a start,

00:17:15.675 --> 00:17:19.040
and in comparing if--
how their timing was with

00:17:19.040 --> 00:17:21.960
their--the start of skyscrapers.
 

00:17:21.960 --> 00:17:24.897
Will Goetzmann:
 Yeah, so look across

00:17:24.897 --> 00:17:27.756
country,
and cross-sectionally,

00:17:27.756 --> 00:17:33.116
you'd like to find conditions
that maybe didn't have this

00:17:33.116 --> 00:17:35.318
financial explosion.
 

00:17:35.318 --> 00:17:38.518
Student:  Perhaps you
might find some exogenous reason

00:17:38.518 --> 00:17:41.663
why they didn't have the capital
markets that are completely

00:17:41.663 --> 00:17:43.690
independent of the other
factors,

00:17:43.690 --> 00:17:45.558
but that's hard to do.
 

00:17:45.558 --> 00:17:46.923
Will Goetzmann:
 Okay, does everybody know

00:17:46.923 --> 00:17:47.549
what endogeneity is?
 

00:17:47.549 --> 00:17:51.210
Everybody who is an Econ.
 

00:17:51.210 --> 00:17:54.180
major and you're a senior or a
junior you probably know.

00:17:54.180 --> 00:17:58.076
Other than that you probably
think it's some kind of horrible

00:17:58.076 --> 00:17:59.048
skin disease.
 

00:17:59.048 --> 00:18:03.282
Endogeneity means that the
factors that you're studying

00:18:03.282 --> 00:18:06.251
could actually be--
it could be some reverse

00:18:06.251 --> 00:18:08.814
causality going on,
or there could be some--a

00:18:08.814 --> 00:18:12.410
common unidentified factor that
could be driving both of them,

00:18:12.410 --> 00:18:14.380
and you have to find some way
of sorting this out.

00:18:14.380 --> 00:18:19.397
The question is--so the one way
to do this is to find some

00:18:19.397 --> 00:18:22.480
independent phenomena to
observe.

00:18:22.480 --> 00:18:25.069
That's what's being proposed.
 

00:18:25.069 --> 00:18:27.380
Any other suggestions?
 

00:18:27.380 --> 00:18:32.336
Here's some college--
Student:  I was just

00:18:32.336 --> 00:18:37.662
going to say that you could
always not only look at the rest

00:18:37.662 --> 00:18:41.424
of the world but look at,
in the United States,

00:18:41.424 --> 00:18:44.479
the development of these types
of bonds and the number of

00:18:44.479 --> 00:18:47.828
skyscrapers like with this,
and I would wager that probably

00:18:47.828 --> 00:18:50.933
the first skyscrapers were not
financed with these types of

00:18:50.933 --> 00:18:52.750
bonds,
which would seem to indicate

00:18:52.750 --> 00:18:55.404
that there was some other factor
at least initially driving

00:18:55.404 --> 00:18:56.640
skyscraper construction.
 

00:18:56.640 --> 00:18:58.782
Will Goetzmann:
 Okay, so if you can find a

00:18:58.782 --> 00:19:01.105
skyscraper that was--
the first skyscraper was--if

00:19:01.105 --> 00:19:03.880
you can show that it wasn't
financed by these bonds than you

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:06.747
could prove that it's possible
to have skyscrapers without the

00:19:06.747 --> 00:19:09.840
financing,
so that's a way to test the

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:11.490
basic proposition.
 

00:19:11.490 --> 00:19:16.626
It may be--it may not--you can
prove that it's not a necessary

00:19:16.626 --> 00:19:19.660
condition if you find one
example.

00:19:19.660 --> 00:19:27.059
One more idea--who's an SOM
student?

00:19:27.059 --> 00:19:30.950
Got one here--no.
 

00:19:30.950 --> 00:19:38.390
You here in the--yes,
gray--charcoal t-shirt.

00:19:38.390 --> 00:19:42.185
Student:  Other than
taking a survey looking at

00:19:42.185 --> 00:19:45.974
multiple cities and how--
when skyscrapers started to be

00:19:45.974 --> 00:19:48.346
built,
and when this capital market

00:19:48.346 --> 00:19:50.880
developed,
I don't think I can really add

00:19:50.880 --> 00:19:52.615
anything else other--
Will Goetzmann:

00:19:52.615 --> 00:19:53.078
 That's good.
 

00:19:53.078 --> 00:19:54.608
Take a look cross-sectionally
at the different cities,

00:19:54.608 --> 00:19:57.328
see if they have,
maybe, access to capital

00:19:57.328 --> 00:20:00.049
markets differently across the
cities,

00:20:00.049 --> 00:20:01.589
and see what the timing is.
 

00:20:01.589 --> 00:20:02.690
That's a good idea.
 

00:20:02.690 --> 00:20:06.568
I'll tell you what we have been
doing.

00:20:06.568 --> 00:20:11.416
We figured that one interesting
issue here is--has to do with

00:20:11.416 --> 00:20:13.759
the size of the bond issue.
 

00:20:13.759 --> 00:20:17.909
If you have a really--if you
have a tiny building and you

00:20:17.909 --> 00:20:21.170
want to go to the public capital
markets,

00:20:21.170 --> 00:20:26.803
do you think an investment bank
is going to give you the time of

00:20:26.803 --> 00:20:27.339
day?
 

00:20:27.339 --> 00:20:30.661
Absolutely not;
there are basic issues of

00:20:30.661 --> 00:20:34.068
economies of scale that have to
do with financing.

00:20:34.068 --> 00:20:37.491
So what we did is we said,
"Let's take a look at the

00:20:37.491 --> 00:20:41.159
size of the bond issue,"
we also looked at the height of

00:20:41.159 --> 00:20:43.585
the building,
but the size of the bond issue

00:20:43.585 --> 00:20:45.220
is the legitimate thing to look
at,

00:20:45.220 --> 00:20:48.369
and presuming that the bigger
the bond issue,

00:20:48.369 --> 00:20:49.779
the bigger the building.
 

00:20:49.779 --> 00:20:53.063
Then we asked,
"Is the interest rate on

00:20:53.063 --> 00:20:56.329
the bond,
that is the rate at which the

00:20:56.329 --> 00:21:00.450
bond was issued,
was that lower or higher for

00:21:00.450 --> 00:21:02.730
bigger buildings?"
 

00:21:02.730 --> 00:21:06.854
What we found pretty strikingly
is that the bigger the building

00:21:06.854 --> 00:21:10.380
the lower the yield,
the lower the cost of capital.

00:21:10.380 --> 00:21:14.311
So if you're thinking about--if
you're a developer and you've

00:21:14.311 --> 00:21:16.398
got a plot,
and you could build two small

00:21:16.398 --> 00:21:19.135
buildings or one big building,
or you could finance it all at

00:21:19.135 --> 00:21:21.883
once or one at a time and you
know that you're going to be

00:21:21.883 --> 00:21:23.859
able to have a lower cost of
capital,

00:21:23.859 --> 00:21:24.900
what are you going to do?
 

00:21:24.900 --> 00:21:26.868
You're going to build one
really big building.

00:21:26.868 --> 00:21:30.798
You can see finance has this
potential,

00:21:30.798 --> 00:21:34.170
maybe to possibly even distort
the way that the--

00:21:34.170 --> 00:21:37.746
the way that cities develop,
because of simple issues like

00:21:37.746 --> 00:21:41.670
the cost of capital,
and those guys sitting around

00:21:41.670 --> 00:21:45.690
the--toasting themselves that we
saw in 1892,

00:21:45.690 --> 00:21:48.828
the creation of that market for
those securities,

00:21:48.828 --> 00:21:54.027
may have had an influence on
the New York skyline during that

00:21:54.027 --> 00:21:55.240
time period.
 

00:21:55.240 --> 00:21:58.333
Here's just a picture,
by the way, of the tall

00:21:58.333 --> 00:22:02.390
buildings in New York and when
they were all constructed.

00:22:02.390 --> 00:22:06.679
You see huge boom during this
period, and than a long malaise

00:22:06.679 --> 00:22:10.111
during the middle of the
century, during wartime,

00:22:10.111 --> 00:22:12.900
and then the market picked back
up.

00:22:12.900 --> 00:22:18.009
I'll tell you one sort of
shocking thing to me is that the

00:22:18.009 --> 00:22:22.761
residential mortgage backed
security market completely

00:22:22.761 --> 00:22:28.500
disappeared in the '30s and that
commercial one building/one bond

00:22:28.500 --> 00:22:33.788
market completely disappeared at
least by 1940 or so.

00:22:33.788 --> 00:22:36.029
I mean there's still bonds that
may exist,

00:22:36.029 --> 00:22:39.008
but when I say disappeared,
they stopped new issues and you

00:22:39.008 --> 00:22:40.960
couldn't easily trade these
things,

00:22:40.960 --> 00:22:42.630
they didn't change hands.
 

00:22:42.630 --> 00:22:44.170
So there are bonds that are
still paying out.

00:22:44.170 --> 00:22:47.200
I have a friend whose
mother--whose family has some

00:22:47.200 --> 00:22:51.078
securities that were used to
build the Empire State Building,

00:22:51.078 --> 00:22:53.750
they're still paying them money
and they're proud to own these

00:22:53.750 --> 00:22:55.868
things,
but these are the fossils of

00:22:55.868 --> 00:22:57.130
the financial world.
 

00:22:57.130 --> 00:23:00.579
What you had is this
extraordinary period of

00:23:00.579 --> 00:23:03.868
innovation in financing of real
estate.

00:23:03.868 --> 00:23:07.698
The shift in the way that
people were able to access

00:23:07.698 --> 00:23:10.452
mortgage money,
and a change in the way the

00:23:10.452 --> 00:23:13.470
developers thought about how
they would build buildings,

00:23:13.470 --> 00:23:17.436
and all of it came to a
grinding horrible end as a

00:23:17.436 --> 00:23:20.108
result of The Great Depression.
 

00:23:20.108 --> 00:23:28.182
Did that market cause the crash
or was it--did the fallout from

00:23:28.182 --> 00:23:32.348
the crash destroy that market?
 

00:23:32.348 --> 00:23:34.808
That's the question we're
asking ourselves today,

00:23:34.808 --> 00:23:35.220
right?
 

00:23:35.220 --> 00:23:38.519
We're saying,
"Well, subprime obviously

00:23:38.519 --> 00:23:42.662
caused the big problem that
we're in and so the foolish

00:23:42.662 --> 00:23:45.573
bankers,
idiots that wanted to own their

00:23:45.573 --> 00:23:48.660
own home and were willing to
borrow to the hilt,

00:23:48.660 --> 00:23:53.229
this horrible evil brew of
people that couldn't plan ahead

00:23:53.229 --> 00:23:58.279
and bankers that were willing to
give them enough rope that they

00:23:58.279 --> 00:24:03.009
could hang themselves,"
that's sort of the theme,

00:24:03.009 --> 00:24:04.720
the drumbeat we're hearing.
 

00:24:04.720 --> 00:24:10.298
You know sort of wonder,
maybe the mortgage market is a

00:24:10.298 --> 00:24:14.950
casualty rather than a cause of
this crash.

00:24:14.950 --> 00:24:23.230
Doug has given you some
readings that--

00:24:23.230 --> 00:24:28.328
kind of a hard reading to slog
through,

00:24:28.328 --> 00:24:30.740
but because--although,
again, if you're an Econ major

00:24:30.740 --> 00:24:33.473
you should be able to snap your
way right through this thing

00:24:33.473 --> 00:24:35.559
because it's got a bunch of
regressions,

00:24:35.559 --> 00:24:38.460
and tables, and plots.
 

00:24:38.460 --> 00:24:42.798
Let me just tell you a little
bit about the idea of this

00:24:42.798 --> 00:24:43.430
paper.
 

00:24:43.430 --> 00:24:47.640
I'm doing it with Liang Peng,
who is a colleague of mine,

00:24:47.640 --> 00:24:52.227
he's now at Colorado and Jackie
Yen, who is a doctoral student

00:24:52.227 --> 00:24:53.130
at Yale.
 

00:24:53.130 --> 00:24:57.208
Jackie is studying to be a
finance professor but she also

00:24:57.208 --> 00:25:01.722
worked in Wall Street for quite
some time and knows a lot about

00:25:01.722 --> 00:25:05.194
these capital markets,
particularly about mortgage

00:25:05.194 --> 00:25:05.528
data.
 

00:25:05.528 --> 00:25:09.318
The question we're asking is a
simple one,

00:25:09.318 --> 00:25:13.849
like many scholars right now,
we want to try and help the

00:25:13.849 --> 00:25:18.220
world understand what the causes
of this crisis are.

00:25:18.220 --> 00:25:21.982
We're in a position that we
don't--I'm not quite sure I know

00:25:21.982 --> 00:25:24.671
what the causes are,
and so the way that we're

00:25:24.671 --> 00:25:27.358
dealing with that is we're
gathering some data and we're

00:25:27.358 --> 00:25:29.900
looking at it and putting
questions to this data.

00:25:29.900 --> 00:25:33.720
The data that we got are
housing indexes.

00:25:33.720 --> 00:25:38.310
Those come from Bob Shiller and
Chip Case who developed these

00:25:38.310 --> 00:25:41.220
when I was a graduate student
here,

00:25:41.220 --> 00:25:44.619
Bob and Chip Case had just
started building these indexes

00:25:44.619 --> 00:25:45.410
of housing.
 

00:25:45.410 --> 00:25:50.825
We really have data going back,
I think they stretch

00:25:50.825 --> 00:25:57.088
back--their data start from
about, well, late '80s or so.

00:25:57.088 --> 00:25:59.970
What they do is they take sales
of housing;

00:25:59.970 --> 00:26:04.420
they take houses that have been
sold twice in a given city,

00:26:04.420 --> 00:26:08.093
and they get thousands of
those, and you can sort of

00:26:08.093 --> 00:26:12.270
figure out what's the best
measure of return to explain all

00:26:12.270 --> 00:26:16.513
of those repeated sales,
so it's actually transactions

00:26:16.513 --> 00:26:18.519
based measures of housing.
 

00:26:18.519 --> 00:26:22.074
We've got those for all the
city--the big cities in the

00:26:22.074 --> 00:26:24.904
country, and metropolitan
statistical areas,

00:26:24.904 --> 00:26:26.880
about 320 or 330 of these.
 

00:26:26.880 --> 00:26:29.872
Then we have some additional
city level information we can

00:26:29.872 --> 00:26:33.136
compare that to,
then we've got mortgage

00:26:33.136 --> 00:26:35.743
issuance by city,
and finally,

00:26:35.743 --> 00:26:39.637
and this is pretty amazing,
for one year for 2006 we took

00:26:39.637 --> 00:26:43.946
all the mortgages that were
issued in the entire country and

00:26:43.946 --> 00:26:47.380
we have detailed data about
those mortgages.

00:26:47.380 --> 00:26:52.455
We figured somewhere buried in
this data we're going to be able

00:26:52.455 --> 00:26:56.059
to get some sense of what the
problem was.

00:26:56.059 --> 00:26:57.730
Here's a chart.
 

00:26:57.730 --> 00:27:07.080
On this axis is past price
growth from 1999 to 2005--end of

00:27:07.080 --> 00:27:08.210
2005.
 

00:27:08.210 --> 00:27:10.288
What did we do?
 

00:27:10.288 --> 00:27:13.680
We took each one of those
cities, we look at that index

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:17.815
that Bob Shiller had created,
and we said--we just plotted

00:27:17.815 --> 00:27:22.750
the total growth that that index
had undergone over the period--

00:27:22.750 --> 00:27:26.220
over the 2000s, up through 2005.
 

00:27:26.220 --> 00:27:29.740
We wanted to look at the hot
markets.

00:27:29.740 --> 00:27:31.700
Which were the really hot
markets?

00:27:31.700 --> 00:27:33.808
Which ones had really grown a
lot?

00:27:33.808 --> 00:27:36.571
You could see some of them had
grown by almost a factor of

00:27:36.571 --> 00:27:39.574
three;
Las Vegas, there are parts of

00:27:39.574 --> 00:27:44.261
California and Nevada,
and Florida that were just off

00:27:44.261 --> 00:27:48.410
the charts, having grown an
amazing amount.

00:27:48.410 --> 00:27:51.476
By the way there are a lot of
cities where there wasn't much

00:27:51.476 --> 00:27:53.785
growth at all,
the whole cluster here of

00:27:53.785 --> 00:27:56.009
cities that had grown by a
factor of--

00:27:56.009 --> 00:28:00.275
well, they had grown 30% but
that was over a long length of

00:28:00.275 --> 00:28:00.788
time.
 

00:28:00.788 --> 00:28:02.578
They're probably growing at
less than 10% per year.

00:28:02.578 --> 00:28:06.555
Well 10% per year over this
time period was actually a

00:28:06.555 --> 00:28:10.230
pretty good investment when you
think about it.

00:28:10.230 --> 00:28:12.650
The stock market was doing
terribly.

00:28:12.650 --> 00:28:15.949
We had just gotten off this
horrible bender from the tech

00:28:15.949 --> 00:28:16.480
bubble.
 

00:28:16.480 --> 00:28:18.440
People said,
"Stocks are terrible,

00:28:18.440 --> 00:28:20.826
I don't want to invest in them
anymore,"

00:28:20.826 --> 00:28:24.023
bonds were a decent investment,
but they were--people were

00:28:24.023 --> 00:28:26.890
really wondering what are we
going to put my money in.

00:28:26.890 --> 00:28:30.125
A lot of people thought
housing, although a modest

00:28:30.125 --> 00:28:34.219
growth in many of these cities,
housing might not be such a bad

00:28:34.219 --> 00:28:34.880
thing.
 

00:28:34.880 --> 00:28:38.804
When you think about it,
if you're sitting in the year

00:28:38.804 --> 00:28:42.578
2000 having just been burned by
the tech bubble,

00:28:42.578 --> 00:28:44.449
and you're saying,
"How am I going to save

00:28:44.449 --> 00:28:45.788
for myself and my family?"
 

00:28:45.788 --> 00:28:49.750
You know, why not put your
money in your house?

00:28:49.750 --> 00:28:52.868
At least you can watch the
asset, you can take care of it,

00:28:52.868 --> 00:28:56.148
you can improve it,
granted you have to pay takes

00:28:56.148 --> 00:29:00.058
on it and you have to fix it up,
and it's not very liquid.

00:29:00.058 --> 00:29:04.457
But you balance these things
off, it might be--it was the new

00:29:04.457 --> 00:29:06.288
asset class of the era.
 

00:29:06.288 --> 00:29:08.827
It was an idea--it was not a
speculative asset,

00:29:08.827 --> 00:29:10.650
it was a savings related asset.
 

00:29:10.650 --> 00:29:12.829
Okay, how about this other axis?
 

00:29:12.829 --> 00:29:19.571
Subprime approvals in 2006;
the log of the dollar amount in

00:29:19.571 --> 00:29:20.828
thousands.
 

00:29:20.828 --> 00:29:25.006
We looked at all of these--we
looked at the rates city by city

00:29:25.006 --> 00:29:26.650
of subprime approvals.
 

00:29:26.650 --> 00:29:31.160
That is, people that had
applied for a subprime mortgage

00:29:31.160 --> 00:29:33.210
and then been approved.
 

00:29:33.210 --> 00:29:39.027
A subprime mortgage means you
don't qualify to get a prime

00:29:39.027 --> 00:29:40.150
mortgage.
 

00:29:40.150 --> 00:29:43.653
To qualify for a prime mortgage
you have to have steady source

00:29:43.653 --> 00:29:46.452
of income,
you have to have a good credit

00:29:46.452 --> 00:29:49.095
rating,
there has to be a good loan to

00:29:49.095 --> 00:29:51.615
value ratio,
that means you aren't trying to

00:29:51.615 --> 00:29:54.471
borrow too much,
you have to have a house that's

00:29:54.471 --> 00:29:57.981
appraised in such a way that the
loan to value ratio is a

00:29:57.981 --> 00:30:00.740
legitimate measure that a bank
can trust.

00:30:00.740 --> 00:30:03.931
If you're not in that
circumstance then you're in

00:30:03.931 --> 00:30:05.858
sub--the world of subprime.
 

00:30:05.858 --> 00:30:13.277
What we see here is subprime
approvals were more frequent in

00:30:13.277 --> 00:30:18.180
markets where the prices had
gone up.

00:30:18.180 --> 00:30:21.500
Why would that be?
 

00:30:21.500 --> 00:30:25.920
Okay I'll ask this as a general
question.

00:30:25.920 --> 00:30:27.670
Why would you expect that?
 

00:30:27.670 --> 00:30:29.838
Yes.
 

00:30:29.838 --> 00:30:32.714
Student:  When you
have--when the prices are higher

