00:34:58.141 --> 00:34:59.510
than 20% or so.
 

00:34:59.510 --> 00:35:04.557
Only one time out of twenty
would you get a shock of more

00:35:04.557 --> 00:35:05.550
than 20%.
 

00:35:05.550 --> 00:35:10.789
How would you get that?
 

00:35:10.789 --> 00:35:14.652
Here we are;
now here's a whole--here are a

00:35:14.652 --> 00:35:18.018
whole bunch of these--the same
exercise.

00:35:18.018 --> 00:35:19.909
I'll tell you a little bit
about the exercise.

00:35:19.909 --> 00:35:21.518
Here's where the econometrics
comes in.

00:35:21.518 --> 00:35:26.027
We take those indexes that
Shiller gave us for all the

00:35:26.027 --> 00:35:29.208
different cities,
these major cities,

00:35:29.208 --> 00:35:33.876
and than we did something that
any red-blooded econometrician

00:35:33.876 --> 00:35:34.809
would do.
 

00:35:34.809 --> 00:35:38.864
We did an auto-regression which
estimates the relationship

00:35:38.864 --> 00:35:41.710
between past growth and future
growth.

00:35:41.710 --> 00:35:46.206
What you see from all these
housing indexes is that past

00:35:46.206 --> 00:35:50.753
trends seem to be followed--
there seems to be a huge amount

00:35:50.753 --> 00:35:54.940
of momentum and inertia in these
movements of these markets,

00:35:54.940 --> 00:35:57.110
even when they're going down.
 

00:35:57.110 --> 00:36:00.309
Once they start--here's
Minneapolis,

00:36:00.309 --> 00:36:02.786
it was going up like this,
incredible auto correlation in

00:36:02.786 --> 00:36:04.771
past trends,
and then of course once it

00:36:04.771 --> 00:36:07.010
starts going down it just keeps
going down.

00:36:07.010 --> 00:36:08.880
This is not a random walk.
 

00:36:08.880 --> 00:36:11.400
Housing doesn't follow a random
walk by any stretch of the

00:36:11.400 --> 00:36:12.019
imagination.
 

00:36:12.019 --> 00:36:13.630
It's very, very predictable.
 

00:36:13.630 --> 00:36:16.344
You could predict,
the models tell you that you

00:36:16.344 --> 00:36:18.469
could predict the housing
prices,

00:36:18.469 --> 00:36:22.759
with a huge degree of
confidence for three years out

00:36:22.759 --> 00:36:27.289
just given about twenty--
fifteen or twenty years worth

00:36:27.289 --> 00:36:28.380
of past data.
 

00:36:28.380 --> 00:36:33.731
All of these pictures show you
that for each city there is a

00:36:33.731 --> 00:36:37.360
line which is the past price
increase.

00:36:37.360 --> 00:36:41.420
That's the--not Las Vegas--went
up like crazy at one point.

00:36:41.420 --> 00:36:44.025
Then there are the two
confidence bands,

00:36:44.025 --> 00:36:47.699
then there's the orange bar
saying what do we expect the

00:36:47.699 --> 00:36:49.170
price trend to be?
 

00:36:49.170 --> 00:36:51.516
But it's not the expectation
that's so important,

00:36:51.516 --> 00:36:54.110
it's this lower bound;
how bad can it get?

00:36:54.110 --> 00:36:57.099
If you're a banker that's the
thing that tells you,

00:36:57.099 --> 00:37:00.090
"Is this loan going to be
a disaster?"

00:37:00.090 --> 00:37:04.126
Every single one of these
cities, virtually,

00:37:04.126 --> 00:37:09.288
the actual price just plunged
right through the banker's

00:37:09.288 --> 00:37:11.260
confidence bands.
 

00:37:11.260 --> 00:37:16.447
If you've got a model that's an
econometric model that's based

00:37:16.447 --> 00:37:20.733
on past price trends,
and you ran that model in 2006

00:37:20.733 --> 00:37:25.070
you wouldn't have been able to
predict any of this crash.

00:37:25.070 --> 00:37:27.862
You would have felt pretty
confident that when you were

00:37:27.862 --> 00:37:32.210
writing those mortgages,
even the subprime mortgage,

00:37:32.210 --> 00:37:36.860
that those were good bonds,
that was a good loan.

00:37:36.860 --> 00:37:42.030
A subprime loan doesn't mean
that the house is bad;

00:37:42.030 --> 00:37:48.530
it just means a borrower is bad.
 

00:37:48.530 --> 00:37:51.230
It's a subprime borrower,
not a subprime house.

00:37:51.230 --> 00:37:53.644
So you say, "Look,
what's the worst that could

00:37:53.644 --> 00:37:54.079
happen?
 

00:37:54.079 --> 00:37:59.659
My borrower can't--we get into
some trouble,

00:37:59.659 --> 00:38:01.539
my borrower can't make the
payments on the house,

00:38:01.539 --> 00:38:04.650
then the bank has to repossess
the house,

00:38:04.650 --> 00:38:06.719
but if the house price isn't
going to move much,

00:38:06.719 --> 00:38:09.306
then what the heck,
we'll just turn around and sell

00:38:09.306 --> 00:38:11.739
the house so we've got good
collateral."

00:38:11.739 --> 00:38:16.530
We all know what happened.
 

00:38:16.530 --> 00:38:20.471
That model turned out--that
econometric model turned out to

00:38:20.471 --> 00:38:22.170
be a complete disaster.
 

00:38:22.170 --> 00:38:28.630
Actually one more point on this.
 

00:38:28.630 --> 00:38:35.373
What do you need for an
