Student:  Data.
 

00:39:03.559 --> 00:39:04.610
Will Goetzmann:  Data.
 

00:39:04.610 --> 00:39:05.309
Okay.
 

00:39:05.309 --> 00:39:09.934
You need data,
and so the data come from

00:39:09.934 --> 00:39:11.949
Robert Shiller.
 

00:39:11.949 --> 00:39:14.938
The fact is,
unless you have those housing

00:39:14.938 --> 00:39:17.489
indexes you can't run this
model.

00:39:17.489 --> 00:39:22.211
The irony of these indexes is
that although they opened a

00:39:22.211 --> 00:39:25.670
world to us of what housing
prices do,

00:39:25.670 --> 00:39:29.702
they also made econometricians
believe that they could estimate

00:39:29.702 --> 00:39:32.239
the risk associated with the
housing.

00:39:32.239 --> 00:39:35.451
Before we had those indexes we
couldn't do any prediction,

00:39:35.451 --> 00:39:38.382
we couldn't do any of this
sophisticated mathematical

00:39:38.382 --> 00:39:39.340
calculations.
 

00:39:39.340 --> 00:39:43.550
We couldn't walk into the
president of the bank and say,

00:39:43.550 --> 00:39:47.887
"Look, we've done a value
at risk calculation using these

00:39:47.887 --> 00:39:51.869
fantastic indexes that tell us
that the probability of us

00:39:51.869 --> 00:39:55.710
losing more than 20% of our
capital is .005."

00:39:55.710 --> 00:39:56.960
You couldn't do it.
 

00:39:56.960 --> 00:39:59.907
Suddenly, with this data,
a little bit of information is

00:39:59.907 --> 00:40:03.123
a really dangerous thing when
you put it in front of somebody

00:40:03.123 --> 00:40:05.750
that knows how to crank through
a regression.

00:40:05.750 --> 00:40:10.059
It's a terrible thing to blame
Bob Shiller,

00:40:10.059 --> 00:40:12.690
the person that forecast this
crash,

00:40:12.690 --> 00:40:16.809
to blame him on the other hand,
for providing the matches that

00:40:16.809 --> 00:40:19.510
allowed people to burn down the
house.

00:40:19.510 --> 00:40:22.974
It was a failure of models but
you can't run the models without

00:40:22.974 --> 00:40:23.590
the data.
 

00:40:23.590 --> 00:40:31.619
I'll just give you a little bit
more flavor for what we do.

00:40:31.619 --> 00:40:34.849
We run a whole bunch of
regressions.

00:40:34.849 --> 00:40:36.804
We're looking for
relationships,

00:40:36.804 --> 00:40:40.465
but mainly what we do is we
divide things up into the world

00:40:40.465 --> 00:40:44.440
of the demand side for loans and
the supply side for loans.

00:40:44.440 --> 00:40:49.704
What we want to ask is,
