00:40:49.704 --> 00:40:52.630
banker that drove the crash?
 

00:40:52.630 --> 00:40:56.713
Or was it the stupid and
avaricious homeowner,

00:40:56.713 --> 00:41:01.250
borrower that drove the crash,
neither, or both.

00:41:01.250 --> 00:41:08.219
Here we have subprime mortgages
and prime mortgages.

00:41:08.219 --> 00:41:11.523
Roughly when we look at
relationships,

00:41:11.523 --> 00:41:13.489
here's what we find.
 

00:41:13.489 --> 00:41:16.949
We find for both subprime and
prime,

00:41:16.949 --> 00:41:21.110
the numbers of applications and
measured by--

00:41:21.110 --> 00:41:25.981
dollars and numbers of
applications were increasing in

00:41:25.981 --> 00:41:27.820
those home prices.
 

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:32.184
So when the home price goes up
you make your forecast of what

00:41:32.184 --> 00:41:36.255
the worst scenario might be,
and if you had a positive

00:41:36.255 --> 00:41:39.742
trend, you would think that
lenders would be more

00:41:39.742 --> 00:41:42.429
comfortable with the bottom
line,

00:41:42.429 --> 00:41:45.360
that they'd be able to get
their money out.

00:41:45.360 --> 00:41:47.027
And borrowers,
if they think,

00:41:47.027 --> 00:41:49.545
"Hey look,
I'm buying a house,

00:41:49.545 --> 00:41:52.590
I'm putting every dime I have
into it,

00:41:52.590 --> 00:41:56.155
but the trends look pretty
good, I should be able to get my

00:41:56.155 --> 00:41:59.476
money out at the other
end," then you ought to see

00:41:59.476 --> 00:42:02.860
a positive relationship between
past price increases and

00:42:02.860 --> 00:42:07.000
applications,
however you want to slice it.

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:10.199
Somebody mentioned--you
mentioned leverage.

00:42:10.199 --> 00:42:13.800
That's exactly what happened.
 

00:42:13.800 --> 00:42:18.373
There was a greater loan to
income requests for--higher

00:42:18.373 --> 00:42:21.929
leverage requests for both of
those two.

00:42:21.929 --> 00:42:27.744
People actually also tended
to--this is loan to income,

00:42:27.744 --> 00:42:32.159
measure of leverage,
not loan to value.

00:42:32.159 --> 00:42:37.480
The loan to value actually
also--the value to loan went up.

00:42:37.480 --> 00:42:38.639
Why is that?
 

00:42:38.639 --> 00:42:41.492
People felt comfortable putting
more of their money into houses

00:42:41.492 --> 00:42:43.699
and than people bought more
expensive houses,

00:42:43.699 --> 00:42:46.909
but the endogeneity issue--who
mentioned that?

00:42:46.909 --> 00:42:48.489
That was a really important
point.

00:42:48.489 --> 00:42:53.230
There were more expensive
houses so that was inevitable.

00:42:53.230 --> 00:42:56.679
So were people being foolish?
 

00:42:56.679 --> 00:42:59.690
Well that's a hard thing to say.
 

00:42:59.690 --> 00:43:03.199
They looked at it as a savings
opportunity.

00:43:03.199 --> 00:43:08.965
You could say this was a crisis
driven by over too much demand

00:43:08.965 --> 00:43:10.289
for savings.
 

00:43:10.289 --> 00:43:13.146
It's just that they didn't save
in--just that the savings

00:43:13.146 --> 00:43:14.369
vehicle was the house.
 

00:43:14.369 --> 00:43:19.018
Were they irrationally
exuberant?

00:43:19.018 --> 00:43:22.985
Well if you look at those
trends maybe I would have been

00:43:22.985 --> 00:43:25.510
fooled by the same trend as
well.

00:43:25.510 --> 00:43:28.530
How about on the banker's side?
 

00:43:28.530 --> 00:43:34.110
Now the banker's job is to say
no, to reject loans.

00:43:34.110 --> 00:43:35.949
What do we find here?
 

00:43:35.949 --> 00:43:39.760
Now the weirdest thing that we
completely--

00:43:39.760 --> 00:43:44.650
that completely shocked us is
that approvals didn't really--

00:43:44.650 --> 00:43:46.750
the rate of approvals for
subprime,

00:43:46.750 --> 00:43:49.309
once we controlled for a lot of
things,

00:43:49.309 --> 00:43:52.690
didn't change as much as we had
expected.

00:43:52.690 --> 00:43:58.188
In fact the rate for approvals
for prime actually went down,

00:43:58.188 --> 00:43:59.960
which is strange.
 

00:43:59.960 --> 00:44:01.630
That means bankers were getting
tougher.

00:44:01.630 --> 00:44:05.755
Well, they were only getting
tougher because the demands were

00:44:05.755 --> 00:44:06.650
increasing.
 

00:44:06.650 --> 00:44:10.313
You have to look at this as,
the environment was changing

00:44:10.313 --> 00:44:13.780
because the demand for loans was
increasing a lot,

00:44:13.780 --> 00:44:17.346
but so that there were--their
approval rates were actually

00:44:17.346 --> 00:44:18.159
going down.
 

00:44:18.159 --> 00:44:22.637
It really doesn't look like
that--it doesn't look like

00:44:22.637 --> 00:44:27.789
irrational exuberance on the
bankers' part for prime loans.

00:44:27.789 --> 00:44:35.501
Mostly on the prime side,
bankers appeared to be behaving

00:44:35.501 --> 00:44:43.349
really pretty rationally,
less so on the subprime side.

00:44:43.349 --> 00:44:49.300
The loan-to-income ratio,
that was going up;

00:44:49.300 --> 00:44:54.980
the value-to-loan ratio was
going down;

00:44:54.980 --> 00:44:58.237
in other words,
people were having to put up

00:44:58.237 --> 00:45:02.327
less of their own cash to own
the home, and people were

